# Summary

We trained a deep-learning model ({{encoder_name}} backbone) that looks at every segmented
cell and decides whether it is a **good** cell worth measuring or a **bad** segmentation
that should be thrown away. On an independent test set of **{{n_test_cells}}** cells the
model performs strongly: it correctly accepts good cells **{{baseline_recall_pct}}** of
the time and correctly discards bad cells **{{baseline_specificity_pct}}** of the time,
with overall accuracy **{{baseline_accuracy_pct}}**. With **selective rejection** (allowing
the model to defer uncertain cells), the accepted subset reaches **{{selective_accuracy_pct}}**
accuracy at **{{coverage_pct}}** coverage.

Applying this filter to the full imaging dataset yields **{{n_good_cells}}** good cells
from **{{n_frogs}}** frogs for morphometry. The typical (median) cell covers
**{{area_median_um2}} $\mu$m$^2$**, with median N/C ratio **{{nc_median}}**. Per-frog mean
cell area spans **{{frog_mean_area_min}}--{{frog_mean_area_max}} $\mu$m$^2$**. Nucleus--cell
scaling is {{scaling_interpretation}}.

# Part A — Baseline classifier (single decision threshold)

### How it decides

The classifier outputs a probability `p(good)` between 0 and 1 for every cell. In
**baseline mode** we keep the cell if **p(good) $\geq$ 0.50** and discard it otherwise.
No cells are deferred.

