# Part B — Adding a "not sure" option (selective rejection)

Baseline mode always produces an answer. For biology it is sometimes safer to defer the
most ambiguous crops.

### How it decides

We split the probability axis into three zones using two thresholds (after temperature
scaling with T = **{{temperature}}**):

- **p(good) $\leq$ {{t_bad}}** $\rightarrow$ **bad** (accepted as bad)
- **p(good) $\geq$ {{t_good}}** $\rightarrow$ **good** (accepted as good)
- **{{t_bad}} < p(good) < {{t_good}}** $\rightarrow$ **rejected / unsure** (deferred)

### Headline metrics — baseline vs selective (test split)

All selective-rejection metrics below are computed **only on cells the model accepted.**

{{selective_comparison_table}}

### Coverage and rejection summary

- Accepted: **{{n_accepted}} / {{n_test_cells}}** cells (**{{coverage_pct}}**)
- Rejected / unsure: **{{n_rejected}} / {{n_test_cells}}**
  - Among rejected: **{{n_rejected_good}}** truly good, **{{n_rejected_bad}}** truly bad

**Intuition.** False negatives drop from **{{baseline_fn}}** to **{{selective_fn}}** under
selective rejection; false positives from **{{baseline_fp}}** to **{{selective_fp}}**.

